04906nam a22005055i 9780773563858DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19931993xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735638587 a10.1515/97807735638582doi  a(DE-B1597)655407  a(OCoLC)732601051  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aR463.N8bM277 1993eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a362.1/09716/090331 aMarble, Allan Everett, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSurgeons, Smallpox, and the Poor :bA History of Medicine and Social Conditions in Nova Scotia, 1749-1799 /cAllan Everett Marble. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tArrival, Settlement, and an Initial Concern for Health Care, 1749 (o.s.) – 1753 (n.s.) -- tA Decade of Military and Naval Surgeons, 1753–1763 -- tPoor Relief Takes Precedence over Health Care, 1763–1775 -- tA New Order of Medical Men: The Loyalists, 1775–1784 -- tHealth Care and Poor Relief at the End of the Century, 1784–1799 -- tAppendices -- tPassengers in the Cornwallis Mess Lists With Health - Care Occupations -- tAn Explanation of Medications and Treatments Administered by Surgeons in Halifax During the Period 1750–53 -- tAn Act to Prevent the Spreading of Contagious Distempers* -- tAn Act to Prevent Importing Impotent, Lame, and Infirm Persons into This Province* -- tLoyalist Physicians and Surgeons who Settled in Nova Scotia During 1783 -- tSummary of Claims for Property and Loss of Income Made by Loyalist Doctors Who Came to Nova Scotia, Compared With the Sums Allowed and the Pensions Awarded by the Loyalist Claims Commissioners -- tThe Indenture of Apprenticeship of William James Allmon -- tPhysicians and Surgeons in Charge of Hospitals in Halifax and Environs, 1749–1799 -- tCauses of Death of Nova Scotians Between 1749 and 1799 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeginning with an account of the settlement of Halifax, Marble documents the care taken by the Lords of Trade and Plantations to provide proper food and health care during the settlers' passage across the Atlantic in May and June of 1749. He chronicles the rendezvous of regiments and ships in Halifax between 1755 and 1763, examining the two smallpox epidemics which followed their arrival. He deals with the treatment of the poor in Nova Scotia between the Seven Years War and the American Revolution, showing that many in this group were camp followers who had been abandoned by regiments that had left Halifax. Financial resources previously directed towards providing medical services for citizens had to be redirected to feed, clothe, and shelter such individuals. A third smallpox epidemic struck Nova Scotia in 1775-76 and, as Marble demonstrates, prevented the Americans from attacking Halifax. He examines the initial unsuccessful attempt to regulate the practice of medicine in Nova Scotia and explores the reasons the region lagged behind Lower Canada and the American colonies in this regard. Marble covers all aspects of health care, including hospitals, the training and practices of physicians and surgeons, the use of patent medicines, and the various types of medical and surgical treatments. As well, he has made a thorough study of individual patients through their wills, diaries, and personal letters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of